stic forenames:  Irish Liam.","English (Essex and Suffolk): variant of   Gower  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Gurr","meanings":["German: derisive nickname for a useless person or a wicked woman, from Middle High German <i>gurre</i> ‘bad mare’.","English (Kent and Middlesex): variant of   Gower   or   Gore  ."]},{"name":"Jowers","meanings":["English (Essex and Suffolk): variant of   Gower  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Goward","meanings":["English (Norfolk): variant of   Gower  , with excrescent <i>-d</i>."]}]},{"name":"Ann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Anne .  In the U.S. <i>Ann</i> is the more frequent spelling."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":19,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":28,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Ann Gower was born in 1530, in Guildford, Surrey, England, her father, John Gower, was 20 and her mother, Mary Ann Palmer, was 20. She married Sir Richard John Gunner in 1550, in Shipton, Glouceste